IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Space Flights
The company IBM (International Business Machines), founded a hundred years ago in New York, initially had a quite complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM only in 1924 - initially it was a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation of the later company IBM laid the merger of four companies, whose history returns until the 1980s of the 19th century.
They owned technologies such as, for example, the famous stick card watches for registration of the work beginning and end.
The architect of this new company became Charles Ranlett Flint, who also had the chairmanship of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the competitor company Thomas J. Watson to help him manage the company.
This leader then even put the founders of IBM into the shadow – based on Watson’s ideas until today, the unbeatable culture and identity of the company.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name already reveals, began with the manufacturing and distribution of all possible machines for the trading – from sausage and cheese cutters to cash.
In the first four decades in which Watson led the company, he doubled its sales to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so essential for the company that he sat in the head chair for forty years, until then he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under its leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, technicians and computers of IBM helped lead NASA flights to the All – to Mercury and Saturn and in 1969 also the famous human flight to the Moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture – the series IBM System/360.
A classic PC, which defined the computer standard of that time, came to the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consultant part of the PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus entered into the business of high-value consulting services and services.
The strategy IBM has been paid over the past three years is the concept “Smart Planet”.
It embodies the intention of intelligent use of technologies in areas not even planned to date, such as improving the situation in transport and city administration.
In the trading sector, IBM recently introduced the Smart Commerce platform to help traders manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in Czech Republic.
In 1932, IBM founded a branch in the Czechoslovakia - as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brünn.
The central central for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague and here is also a world-level top research team dealing with voice recognition technology.
