Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five authorised state travel agencies in the ČSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies sold at the time only travel to the socialist eastern block countries, and at the time only chosen people were allowed in the west.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean Peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A light exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when you were allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia hit a prowest course and therefore the trips to Yugoslavia were strongly restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that it was not even allowed to travel freely to citizens of the Eastern Bloc (so the Czechoslovakians) within the socialist countries.
If, for example, a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even at that time, the travel agencies also offered travel to the west, but then you had to take huge snakes in purchase or even stay in the sleeping bag before the travel agency, or at least have "good known" in the travel agency.
The thing hasn't been doing so for a long time.
The so-called foreign exchange – the condition for an exit to the West – was granted only “politically reliable” people – the others were not allowed to travel.
The Czechoslovakian currency was not freely exchangeable currency, so without currency currency it would have been impossible to raise the necessary financial funds (western currency) for a trip to the West.
Therefore, most Czechs have spent their holidays in the country, no wonder that the Czechs have bought countless weekend houses and dats – a custom that continues until today.
The tent revolution of 1989 followed a travel revolution of the Czechs on the foot.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the level of all things, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox that you are not aware of today is the fact that you could not travel to the most popular Czech vacation country until 1989, because it was part of the Yugoslavia.
From the early 90s of the last century, the currency obligation was abolished in the neighbouring Western European countries, creating a huge wave of short visits especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks couldn’t get enough from their trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to be there at least a few days.
So the Czech holidaymen slept in the tent in the park when they traveled to Paris, because who would have had the money for a hotel or a pension at the time.
A typical feature in Czech foreign trips was at the time a fully packed suitcase with conserves, beer and lasting sausage etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech Crown - after decades our tourists were finally able to shop the Western currency freely.
Our livelihood and therefore the average salaries increased, which in 1997 entered into another important moment.
Thanks to the increased demands for travel, the travel agencies after 1997 began regularly preparing travel through charter flights, making flight travels incredibly constrained thanks to the opportunity to negotiate quantitative discounts.
In the late 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the US, had already currency-free payment traffic with all the highly developed countries in the world, making travel even easier.
