Facebook is also constantly applying the data of its own population.
The site’s data team has created statistics on relationship status and Valentine’s Day, election participation in the 2010 intermediate elections and a national happiness index (which were primarily used information that only Facebook has access - masters of digital freedom know for a long time that the site should make its large data background available for other research purposes.)
However, Facebook users know that the site watches them, whether they want it or not, and to be able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, you’ll let the site expedite your own personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strictly defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, everything is allowed online.
