Asphalt from UNAM prevents blow holes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University of UNAM, developed with polymers modified asphalts to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If it would be aware of the signs that come from the road cover, it would not be necessary to repair almost 200,000 holes if the rain season in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (the city area of Mexico Valley) is completely breaking out, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the University of Chemistry (FQ), warns and securews.
In his lecture "holes of the technical perspective", which he held as a chemistry on the occasion of the International Year, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for designing asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but which has greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climate, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behavior of the road coating and thus avoid the appearance of holes.
He explained that asphalt - the heaviest part of oil - is a hydrocarbon compound of which one part has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malthenes.
Adhesive behavior of the asphalt means that it behaves at high temperatures of almost 180° C. as a liquid, at 120° C. it is very fluid and almost solid at 50° C. while it becomes brief at very low temperatures.
“This means that the asphalt’s resistance on the roads is not equal, but changes on a day depending on weather conditions and temperature changes,” the chemical engineer said.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City had a majority of flexible road covering, composed of six material layers, including the last three asphalts.
Between the upper layers lies a wear layer of asphalt, which consists of small, baded in asphalt and then reinforced stones.
Each single stone of this wear layer has been baked in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on and forces are generated, this layer allows for a good distribution of forces in the road coating.
"If it was modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," said the chemistry engineer.
"Above the wear layer," he explained, "a last layer will be designed, the so-called carrier layer consisting of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also baked in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need greater mechanical strength than the wear layer and it must make friction.
The street coating receives and distributes most forces, the carrier layer also requires an appropriate thickness and the material it consists of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, in particular moisture and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to be considered, especially water, because it significantly impairs the behavior of the wear layer.
When the ground is moist, water enters the layer and only exits difficult again, causing a dissipation of all layers of the road layer and as a result the appearance of holes.
When a blow hole arises, he said, "the cover layer will first be removed, while the wear layer will only be affected afterwards. But the damage does not arise immediately, but it is a process that should be maintained in the first signs by adequate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) stated that the vehicle load is another important cause of the occurrence of holes, which is why the thickness of each layer of the road coating must always be relative to the vehicle load, and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with to avoid frequent holes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that many research works were still waiting for themselves, for example, about asphalt emulsions that are already on the market in other countries, and with which the crash holes were easily repaired without using high temperatures.
