North Stream, New Gate to Russian Gas in Europe
The gas transmission line Nord Stream, which runs on the base of the Baltic Sea and connects the Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is intended to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to make this event with glory and glory.
More than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, have last Tuesday on the Baltic Sea Coast under orchestral sound and with the opening of the new gas broadcast Nord Stream, which connects Russia and Germany directly under the sea level.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his colleague Mark Rutte from the Netherlands have symbolically jointly turned the control of the valve that transports Russian gas to the Western European network.
The new gas transmission line is intended to deliver 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gas annually through a first 1,224 km-length pipeline that connects the St. Petersburg region with Mecklenburg Prepommern.
A second pipeline that allows a total delivery of 55 billion cubic meters of gas – the equivalent of the total French consumption – will be completed at the end of 2012.
And the eventuality of the construction of a third line is already left on its own path.
For Gazprom, the timely and accurate completion of this huge building is a victory.
The project was very controversial in Poland and the Baltic states.
The Nord-Stream pipeline will, in fact, enable direct gas delivery to Germany, avoiding any track track by third countries (Poland or Ukraine) on the land.
For this reason, these two countries lose a little of their power: it will now be more difficult for them to exercise pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, the most committed to the debate, was not refrained to compare the North Stream pipeline with a "new German-Soviet pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the purpose of Poland's occupation in 1939.
This means that the topic is politically first sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even higher supply security by supporting this Russian project.
This, however, is at the expense of the discharge of European energy, as the project has broken a breach between Western and Eastern Europeans.
Russia has finished in almost five years to enforce its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, western countries that have strong gas consumption and their gas stocks go to the snow.
“This gas transmission is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that combines us organically,” François Fillon confirmed in the opening of the gas transmission by pointing out in which degree the large gas contracts are also important by political and economic sides.
All of this explains the broad smile of the Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin in terms of gas delivery.
The construction of this gas transmission line is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater line is made of steel with concrete coating, which is intended to protect it from ship bodies.
It rests on the sea ground, at about 200 m depth.
During their construction, it had to be removed from the Second World War dating mine fields.
“About hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed for caution,” said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
Moreover, increased measures to protect the fauna and flora had to be taken.
The line is a long serpent made of metal, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which is interrupted throughout the entire length by nothing: neither by valves nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was provided outside the coast of Sweden, but the project managers have taken away from it because the Sweden had little struggled to see a Russian state society permanently settled at the height of their coasts.
"In the case of a variety, we close the gas transmission in less than a minute," Jens Müller said.
Thus, in the case of a leak, the gas in the gas remote line is dismissed into the air.
However, this case is considered little likely by the constructors, as the seams were estimated to be consistent by a leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas transmission line is guaranteed by both a underwater robot which is controlled for external observation purposes from a sea ship, as well as by a device circulating inside the gas transmission line.
It has the shape of a cigar, miβt a meter diameter, is introduced into the interior of the pipeline and moved by the gas pressure.
After three full days of movement through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device delivers the most accurate information on possible deformations of the metal upon arrival.
The gas transmission line was designed to work for fifty years without having to undergo even the least repair.
The gas circulation is easily guaranteed by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the access point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five societies have united their forces to implement this project.
However, the leadership remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF are joined here (each to 15.5%), as well as the Dutch gas unies and the French company group GDF Suez (each to 9%).
These five companies have formed a company community called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas transmission.
She has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where the tax is particularly favorable.
Gazprom has then rented the entire capacity of its gas transportation, in terms of extendable twenty-year agreement.
"Gazprom will pay for the overall capacity, no matter how large the amount of really transported gas fails," Jens Müller said.
The financing of the gas transmission construction was secured to 30% by shareholders and to 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of work should amount to EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amount was 240 million.
However, minority shareholders are committed to recovering their expenses, as Gazprom alone carries the risk of liability.
The gas transmission line comes from the Baltic Sea on a sandy, pine-forested coastline at Lubmin.
The 4.5 meters high valves form the gas outlet forces.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the coming gas before it is transferred to the German gas transmission lines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with a million cubic meters of Russian gas per hour.
With full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
